Pain awakens us at times--sometimes to make space for the joy that might come after. https://t.co/VCnjTz6Cbj

Because in the end, those painful experiences get to be whatever you can make of them.

The things that caused us pain were bad. But the fact that we were in pain? It's just a fact we carry with us. It's an experience that made us who we are.

What if in Dexter season 10, Lumen enters Harrison's life and becomes a mother figure? We saw his conflict with a father for a killer. What about a mom? And what about one who says she only kills men who hurt women?

After the Trinity Killer? That's exactly what would hook him.

MFA and Promising Young Woman both showcase the devastating real-world consequences women tend to face when we fight back.

Lumen didn't really face those consequences. We didn't need her to--it wasn't her show. But what if she returns in season 10? And what if she never stopped?

So the next season of Dexter needs to feature a new kind of killer. One like the anti-heroes in the stunning films MFA, Promising Young Woman, and to a limited degree Lumen/Julia Stiles in Dexter season 5.
Well we’re long past the point when a killer with no relatable motive will play well. Even on Dexter, Showtime got one more shot at those, and Clancy Brown killed it.
But what gets him to come out of hiding? What makes Harrison call on his Dark Passenger/Dad/Dexter?

Perhaps Harrison decides he WON’T kill—and that is his conflict. Fulfill Dexter’s mission without the death. His own father, after all, showed him redemption is possible for almost anyone. So he starts off hoping to redeem bad people.

What’s a worthy cause for Harrison to choose to kill? Or at least to intervene in the path of an evil murderer? 

Well first he needs his own GOAL/MOTIVATION/CONFLICT. Then an adversary to make him hate how hard life can be.

The obvious way to continue the show is for Dexter’s son to carry on the mantle. He’ll need a worthy cause to bring out the skills and impulses he now carries. Dexter, of course, will be present as his Dark Passenger. 

(Deb can still cameo too on a super meta episode)

That’s also why the new finale felt so deeply YES. The season started off with an appropriate amount of shame for those last two seasons. Even the character of Dexter could barely stand to remember how awful they turned out.

The original Dexter finale (season 8) disappointed me because he was never supposed to get away with it—but only because he’s supposed to die a hero. In the real world, men DO get away with it. Violence doesn’t end them.

Tough place for the new Dexter to start from--and yet!
